HEADWORD: Sedum
<hw>Se"dum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L.
<ets>sedere</ets> to sit; so called in allusion to the manner in which
the plants attach themselves to rocks and walls.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants, mostly perennial, having
succulent leaves and cymose flowers; orpine; stonecrop.</def>
<rj><au>Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

